#Text=Register a Car in Florida
#Text=Registering a car in Florida for the first time can seem intimidating -- there ’s a lot of paperwork !
#Text=Luckily , Florida ’s car registration process is pretty easy to figure out .
#Text=All you have to do is make sure you have the correct paperwork , then head to the Florida Department of Highway Safety and Motor Vehicles ( DHSMV ) to finish up your registration !
#Text=Steps
#Text=Gathering Your Paperwork
#Text=Check your Florida license .
#Text=You ca n’t register a car in Florida unless you have a valid Florida ID , so make sure your card is updated and unexpired .
#Text=If you ’ve just moved to Florida from another state , have your old license transferred over .
#Text=You can register a car in your name if you only have a permit , but you have to be at least 18 years old .
#Text=Make sure you have Florida insurance for your car .
#Text=Your car will need to be insured in the state of Florida before you register it .
#Text=Talk to your insurance agent or add a policy online to have your insured .
#Text=You ’ll need to bring proof of insurance to the DHSMV , so make sure you have a printed copy of your policy that includes the VIN and your policy number .
#Text=Bring or apply for your car ’s title .
#Text=If you already have the car titled in your name , bring the title with you when you register it .
#Text=If you do n’t , you can apply for the title and registration at the same time in the state of Florida .
#Text=The only additional paperwork you need is an application for a car title , which is available at the DHSMV .
#Text=Have your car ’s VIN and odometer inspected .
#Text=Florida law requires that you have the vehicle inspection number and odometer reading certified if you buy a new car or bring an out-of-state car into Florida .
#Text=You can get an inspection form from any Florida DHSMV office or website .
#Text=Police officers , military officers , car dealers , and notary publics can verify your car ’s VIN and odometer readings .
#Text=Some DHSMV offices will perform the inspection for you , but not all of them do it .
#Text=Be sure to ask first .
#Text=You can go to any police station or military base and ask for an inspection , but you have to have the form with you .
#Text=Bring cash or a major credit card to pay the registration fee .
#Text=Registration fees in Florida vary by the weight of the car and whether or not it ’s from out of state .
#Text=Most new registrations in Florida are $ 225 , but new cars and leases may be subject to sales taxes and other fees .
#Text=Visiting the DHSMV
#Text=Locate the nearest DHSMV in your county .
#Text=It ’s important to register your car in the county you actually live in .
#Text=Check the DHSMV website for a list of locations in your county , and choose the one closest to you .
#Text=Visit in the morning in the middle of the week if possible .
#Text=If you can time your visit to avoid crowds , do it !
#Text=The DHSMV can get very busy .
#Text=If you have to visit during a busy time like late afternoon or Saturday , make sure you have time to wait .
#Text=Some locations let you make an appointment online or by calling the location directly .
#Text=Check in at the front desk .
#Text=Most DHSMV offices require you to check in at the front desk before waiting .
#Text=They ’ll ask you what you ’re there for and take a quick look at your paperwork to make sure it ’s all together .
#Text=Take a number .
#Text=You ’ll be assigned a number when you finish checking in .
#Text=Wait until you ’re number is called .
#Text=Do n’t worry if the numbers seem to be going out of order -- they ’re separated into different categories to make the lines move faster .
#Text=Go to the window when your number is called .
#Text=Each number will be assigned a window .
#Text=When yours is called , go to the clerk ’s window that matches your number .
#Text=They ’ll be the one to take care of your registration .
#Text=Present your registration documents to the clerk .
#Text=Give the clerk all your paperwork and the money for your fee .
#Text=They ’ll handle the registration for you .
#Text=You probably wo n’t need to do anything but wait for a few minutes and sign your paperwork .
#Text=Then , you 'll be ready to go home !
#Text=Finalizing Your Registration
#Text=Wait for the final registration to arrive in the mail .
#Text=Some counties give you the full registration paperwork at the DHSMV , but others send it to you in the mail later .
#Text=If you have to wait for yours , keep an eye on the mailbox !
#Text=Meanwhile , you can keep your DHSMV receipt in your car for proof of registration .
#Text=Put the registration sticker on the top right corner of your license plate .
#Text=Your registration will come with a little sticker with the year written on it .
#Text=Put the sticker on the top right corner of your plate to avoid being pulled over .
#Text=Florida only requires a rear license plate , so you ’ll only have one sticker .
#Text=Make a copy of your registration for safekeeping .
#Text=It ’s a good idea to have a backup copy of your registration in case it ’s lost or stolen .
#Text=Often , your registration will come with multiple copies , but if it does n’t , make a photocopy for your personal records .
#Text=Place the registration in your car .
#Text=Your actual registration should be put in your car so you can show it in case you ’re pulled over .
#Text=Most people keep theirs in the car ’s glove compartment , but anywhere safe and dry will work .
#Text=Tips
#Text=If you bought your car from a dealership , ask them if they can do the registration for you .
#Text=Florida allows new and certified pre-owned dealerships to register a car on a new owner ’s behalf .
#Text=Florida permits certain drivers to use a courier service to register their cars .
#Text=Talk to the DHSMV to see if you ’re eligible .
#Text=Quick Summary
